ll of the Nine Hostages (Niall Noígíallach), a legendary 5th-century king of Ireland. Their traditional base is Tyrconnell (i.e. Donegal)."],"variants":[{"name":"O'Donell","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Donnell  ."]},{"name":"O'Donnel","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Donnell  ."]},{"name":"O'Daniel","meanings":["Irish: variant of   O'Donnell  , influenced by the Biblical name   Daniel  , to which it is etymologically unrelated."]},{"name":"O'Donald","meanings":["Irish: Scotticized form of   O'Donnell  . The Irish personal name <i>Domhnall</i> was Latinized as <i>Donaldus</i>, which is the source of <i>Donald</i>, the form of the personal name used in English in Scotland, though not in Ireland. The form <i>O'Donald</i> is therefore a 19th-century hybrid. Compare   Donald  ."]},{"name":"Donald","meanings":["Scottish: shortened form of   McDonald   (<i>Mac Dhomhnaill</i>), from the Gaelic personal name <i>Domhnall</i>; found in 13th- and 14th-century Scotland as <i>Dofnald</i>, <i>Douenald</i>, <i>Dufenald</i>, and <i>Donald</i>.","Irish (Ulster): possibly also a shortened and altered form of Irish   O'Donell  ."]}]},{"name":"Turlough","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Toirdhealbhach ."],"variants":[{"name":"Toirdhealbhach","meanings":["Traditional name, apparently from a byname meaning ‘instigator’, from <i>toirdhealbh</i> ‘prompting’. It was the name of a High King of Ireland who died in  1156 ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Turlough O'Donnell, Lord of Tirconnell was born in 1350, in Donegal, County Donegal, Ireland as the son of missing generations , King of Tyrconnell. He had at least 1 son with Miss O'Doherty. He died in 1422, in Donegal, County Tipperary, Ireland, at the age of 72."},"et":{"1350–1422":"1350–1422","1388–1429":"1388–1429","1370–Female":"1370–Surnud","1380–1439":"1380–1439","1392–1439":"1392–1439","1427–1505":"1427–1505","1404–Male":"1404–Surnu